'''Jhon Andrés Córdoba Copete''' ({{IPA|es|ɟʝoŋ ˈkoɾðoβa}}; born 11 May 1993) is a Colombian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Russian Premier League]] club [[FC Krasnodar|Krasnodar]] and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]].

A powerful striker noted for his pace and strength, Córdoba began his senior career with [[Envigado F.C.|Envigado]] before moving abroad to [[Chiapas F.C.|Chiapas]] in Mexico in 2012. After spells in Spain with [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] and [[Granada CF|Granada]], and in Germany with [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]], he joined [[1. FC Köln|Köln]] in 2017. There, he finished as the club’s top scorer and secured promotion to the [[Bundesliga]]. He later played for [[Hertha BSC]] before transferring to [[FC Krasnodar]] in 2021, where he helped the club win their first [[Russian Premier League]] title in 2025. Subsequently, Córdoba was recognised as [[Footballer of the Year in Russia (Sport-Express)|Russian Footballer of the Year]].

At international level, Córdoba was part of the Colombia U20 side that won the [[South American Youth Football Championship|South American U20 Championship]] in 2013. He made his senior debut in 2019 and has since earned over 15 caps, featuring at the [[2024 Copa América]], where Colombia finished runner-ups.

==Club career==

===Envigado and professional breakthrough===
A youth product of [[Envigado F.C.|Envigado]], Córdoba made his senior debut in 2009, scoring on his debut against Itagüí.<ref>https://www.elcolombiano.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/jhon-cordoba-debuto-con-gol-en-envigado-2009-LI2842230</ref> He broke through during the 2011 Torneo Finalización, notably scoring a brace in a 3–2 defeat away to [[Once Caldas]] on 1 October 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/330396/envigado-once-caldas|title=Once Caldas 3-2 Envigado (Oct 1, 2011) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> and netting the winner against [[Independiente Medellín]] two weeks later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/330404/independiente-medellin-envigado|title=Envigado 1-0 Ind. Medellín (Oct 15, 2011) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He remained a starter into the 2012 Apertura, finishing as Envigado’s top league scorer with six goals in 16 matches.<ref>https://caracol.com.co/radio/2012/06/18/deportes/1340004000_709161.html</ref>

===Chiapas===
On 9 July 2012, Córdoba moved to Mexico, joining [[Querétaro F.C.|Querétaro]] and being loaned immediately to [[Chiapas F.C.|Jaguares de Chiapas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://futnsoccer.com/2012/07/04/colombian-drogba-to-jaguares-of-chiapas/|title=Colombian 'Drogba' to Jaguares of Chiapas|first=Kevin|last=Torres|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He made his Liga MX debut on 20 July 2012 against [[Tigres UANL]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/348125/tigres-uanl-chiapas|title=Tigres 4-0 Chiapas (Jul 20, 2012) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> and scored his first Liga MX goal in a 4–0 home win over [[San Luis F.C.|San Luis]] on 7 October 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/348019/san-luis-chiapas|title=Chiapas 4-0 San Luis (Oct 7, 2012) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He went on to score three goals in total for Chiapas during the 2012–13 campaign.

===Espanyol (loan)===
On 2 September 2013, Córdoba joined [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] on a one-year loan with an option to buy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record.com.mx/futbol-futbol-internacional/jhon-cordoba-es-presentado-en-el-espanyol|title=Jhon Córdoba es presentado en el Espanyol|date=13 September 2013|website=www.record.com.mx|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He scored his first La Liga goal for the club on 30 November 2013 in a 2–1 loss away to [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/373074/real-sociedad-espanyol|title=Real Sociedad 2-1 Espanyol (Nov 30, 2013) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> His second league goal came on 25 January 2014 in a 2–2 draw against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/373010/espanyol-valencia|title=Valencia 2-2 Espanyol (Jan 25, 2014) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He finished the season with four goals, proving a reliable attacking option.

===Granada===
On 12 August 2014, Córdoba signed a five-year deal with [[Granada CF|Granada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2014/08/12/primera/1407849862_697493.html|title=Acuerdo con el Querétaro por Jhon Córdoba: firma cinco años|date=12 August 2014|website=Diario AS|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He scored the winner in a 1–0 victory over [[Athletic Bilbao]] at San Mamés on 20 September 2014, converting a defensive error on his first start for the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/402593/granada-athletic-club|title=Granada 1-0 Athletic (Sep 20, 2014) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He later described it as “my debut as a starter” and said he took the opportunity by scoring.<ref>https://www.marca.com/futbol/granada/2014/09/22/541ffeb3e2704ec4198b4581.html</ref>

===Mainz 05===
Córdoba joined [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] on loan from Granada on 31 August 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.futbolred.com/colombianos-en-el-exterior/jhon-cordoba-fue-cedido-del-granada-al-mainz-de-alemania-73145|title=Jhon Córdoba fue cedido del Granada al Mainz, de Alemania|first=Casa Editorial El|last=Tiempo|website=futbolred.com|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> and on 2 March 2016 scored the late winner in a 2–1 upset at [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/mar/02/mainz-bayern-munich-bundesliga-match-report|title=Bayern Munich suffer shock home defeat by Mainz’s Jhon Córdoba|date=2 March 2016|accessdate=18 September 2025|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Mainz exercised their option to sign him permanently in May 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/alemania/nota/_/id/2679473/mainz-compra-a-jhon-cordoba-ex-delantero-de-jaguares|title=Mainz compra a Jhon Córdoba, ex de Jaguares|date=18 May 2016|website=ESPNdeportes.com|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He also scored in Mainz’s 3–2 UEFA Europa League group stage win against Qabala on 29 September 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2019435--viktoria-plzen-vs-astra/|title=History: Viktoria Plzeň 1-2 Astra &#124; UEFA Europa League 2016/17|website=UEFA.com|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref>

===1. FC Köln===
On 28 June 2017, Córdoba transferred to [[1. FC Köln]] on a four-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://es.besoccer.com/noticia/el-koln-paga-15-millones-por-jhon-cordoba|title=El Köln paga 15 millones por Jhon Córdoba|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> In the [[2018–19 2. Bundesliga|2018–19]] season he scored 20 league goals as Köln won the title and promotion. On 6 May 2019 he scored a hat-trick in a 4–0 win over [[SpVgg Greuther Fürth]], clinching the championship.<ref>https://www.kicker.de/greuther-fuerth-gegen-fc-koeln-2019-bundesliga-2-4262174/analyse</ref> On 18 January 2020 he registered his first [[Bundesliga]] brace in a 3–1 win over [[VfL Wolfsburg]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/548210/vfl-wolfsburg-fc-cologne|title=Cologne 3-1 Wolfsburg (Jan 18, 2020) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref>

===Hertha BSC===
On 15 September 2020, Córdoba joined [[Hertha BSC]] on a four-year contract.<ref>https://www.herthabsc.com/en/news/2020/09/cordoba-transfer-2021</ref> He scored on his Bundesliga debut for the club in a 4–1 away win at [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] on 19 September 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/578018/cambridge-united-birmingham-city|title=Cambridge 1-0 Birmingham (Sep 5, 2020) Final Score|website=ESPN|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He finished the season as the club’s joint-top scorer with seven goals.

===Krasnodar===
On 18 July 2021, Hertha announced an agreement to sell Córdoba to [[FC Krasnodar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.herthabsc.com/en/news/2021/07/cordoba-leaves|title=Jhon Córdoba leaves Hertha BSC &#124; Hertha BSC|date=23 July 2021|website=www.herthabsc.com|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> He signed a four-year contract with Krasnodar on 23 July 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fckrasnodar.ru/en/team/news/object/?object_id=139743|title=Jhon Córdoba Joined FC Krasnodar. FC Krasnodar Official site|website=fckrasnodar.ru|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> His contract was suspended in March 2022 amid the league’s hiatus, before he returned to action later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fckrasnodar.ru/team/news/object/?object_id=141382|title="Краснодар" приостановил контракты с несколькими игроками|website=Официальный сайт ФК «Краснодар»|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> On 5 November 2024, Krasnodar announced his extension through 30 June 2027.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sportbox.ru/Vidy_sporta/Futbol/Russia/premier_league/spbnews_NI2130060_Krasnodar_podpisal_novyj_kontrakt_s_napadajushhim_Dzhonom_Kordoboj|title="Краснодар" подписал новый контракт с нападающим Джоном Кордобой|date=5 November 2024|website=news.sportbox.ru|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> In the 2024–25 season he scored in the decisive final-round win over Dynamo Moscow as Krasnodar clinched their first Russian Premier League title,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caracol.com.co/2025/06/28/jhon-cordoba-fue-premiado-con-el-mejor-gol-y-como-mejor-jugador-en-liga-premier-de-rusia-2025/|title=Jhon Córdoba fue premiado con el mejor gol y como mejor jugador en Liga Premier de Rusia 2025|first=Santiago Mojica|last=Alarcón|date=27 June 2025|website=Caracol Radio|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref> and was later voted the league’s Footballer of the Year by fellow players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/colombia/deportes/2025/06/28/el-delantero-colombiano-jhon-cordoba-arraso-con-el-krasnodar-en-la-gala-del-futbol-ruso-estos-fueron-los-premios-que-recibio/|title=El delantero colombiano Jhon Córdoba arrasó con el Krasnodar en la gala del fútbol ruso: estos fueron los premios que recibió|first=Por Carlos|last=Pulido|date=28 June 2025|website=infobae|accessdate=18 September 2025}}</ref>

On 30 November 2025, Córdoba scored his 69th goal for Krasnodar, becoming the top scorer in club history, overtaking [[Fyodor Smolov]]. With the same goal, he also took the top spot in club history for goals plus assists with 96.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sports|url=https://www.sports.ru/football/1116996221-kordoba-stal-luchshim-bombardirom-v-istorii-krasnodara-forvard-takzhe-.html|title=Кордоба стал лучшим бомбардиром в истории "Краснодара", опередив Смолова. Форвард также стал лучшим по "гол+пас", у него 96 (69+27) очков|date=30 November 2025|language=ru}}</ref>

On 21 March 2026, Córdoba scored four goals against [[FC Pari Nizhny Novgorod|Pari Nizhny Novgorod]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Russian Premier League|url=https://premierliga.ru/matches/16138/?category=lineups|title=Матч Краснодар – Пари НН {{!}} 2025/26, 22 тур {{!}} РПЛ|date=21 March 2026|access-date=21 March 2026|language=ru}}</ref> He became the [[2025–26 Russian Premier League]] top scorer with 17 goals.<ref name="top2526">{{cite web|publisher=Sports.ru|url=https://www.sports.ru/football/1117173164-kordoba-s-17-golami-stal-luchshim-bombardirom-rpl-sperczyan-s-16-pered.html|title=Кордоба с 17 голами стал лучшим бомбардиром РПЛ, Сперцян с 16 передачами – лучшим ассистентом|date=17 May 2026|access-date=17 May 2026|language=ru}}</ref>

==International career==

=== Youth ===

==== 2013 South American Youth Championship ====
Córdoba was selected to wear the number 9 jersey to represent Colombia at the [[2013 South American Youth Championship]]. He scored the decisive goal in the opening match against [[Paraguay national under-20 football team|Paraguay]], securing a 1-0 victory. In the following game against [[Bolivia national under-20 football team|Bolivia]], he netted two goals in a commanding 6-0 win despite missing several promising opportunities. Consequently, he was not selected for the final group stage match against [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina]], as Colombia had already secured a spot in the next round. Córdoba scored the winning goal in a 1-0 victory over [[Uruguay national under-20 football team|Uruguay]], propelling Colombia to the top of their group. Following their triumph in the South American championship, he tallied four goals, significantly contributing to his nation's success. This achievement made him Colombia's second-highest scorer in the tournament, just behind [[Juan Fernando Quintero]], who scored five goals.

====2013 U-20 FIFA World Cup====
In the opening match against Australia, Córdoba missed several opportunities while Colombia trailed 1-0. However, he redeemed himself by scoring in the 78th minute, securing a 1–1 draw.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130626060002/http://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=259235/match=300232808/index.html?intcmp=livecoverage_box_u20worldcup_en Colombia 1–1 Australia]; FIFA.com, 22 June 2013</ref> In the final group match against El Salvador, Córdoba successfully converted a penalty, contributing to a 3-0 victory. He played in the round of 16 match against South Korea, where Colombia was eliminated in a penalty shootout following a 1–1 draw.

=== Senior ===
He was first called up in the preliminary list for [[Exhibition game|friendly matches]] against [[Chile national football team|Chile]] and [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] on 12 and 15 October 2019 respectively. In 2020, he was called up to the Colombia preliminary squad for [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] and [[Chile national football team|Chile]] on 26 and 31 March 2020 respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lista de convocados Selección Colombia Masculina de Mayores para amistosos – Federación colombiana de fútbol |url=https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2019/11/06/lista-de-convocados-seleccion-colombia-masculina-de-mayores-para-amistosos/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230606230235/https://fcf.com.co/index.php/2019/11/06/lista-de-convocados-seleccion-colombia-masculina-de-mayores-para-amistosos/ |archive-date=2023-06-06 |access-date=2025-04-16 |website=fcf.com.co |language=es}}</ref> However, he made his first appearance for the senior team as late as 2023.

==Style of play==
Córdoba is a striker noted for his physical attributes, including height and strength, as well as for his shooting ability and pace. His stature has contributed to his effectiveness in aerial play, and he has occasionally been compared to Didier Drogba.<ref name="futnsoccer.com">[http://futnsoccer.com/2012/07/04/colombian-drogba-to-jaguares-of-chiapas/ Colombian ‘Drogba’ to Jaguares of Chiapas]; FutN Soccer, 4 July 2012</ref><ref name="urgente24.com">[http://www.urgente24.com/209426-europa-viene-a-la-caza-de-jovenes-talentos-del-sudamericano Europa viene a la 'caza' de jóvenes talentos del Sudamericano (Europe comes to 'hunt' Sudamerican talents)]; Urgente 24, 9 January 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[http://www.goal.com/es/news/3522/talentos-de-importaci%C3%B3n/2012/06/12/3167835/jhon-c%C3%B3rdoba-el-drogba-que-tiene-envigado-y-todo-colombia Jhon Córdoba, el Drogba que tiene Envigado y todo Colombia (Jhon Córdoba, the Drogba who Envigado and all Colombia has)]; Goal.com, 12 June 2012 {{in lang|es}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Córdoba's father [[Manuel Acisclo Córdoba|Manuel]] was also a professional football striker.<ref name="ET">{{cite web|publisher=El Tiempo|author=Duque Soto, Leonardo|trans-title=Didier Drogba is my football benchmark admits Jhon Córdoba|title="Didier Drogba es mi referente en el fútbol", confesó Jhon Córdoba|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/CMS-11344702|language=es|date=13 March 2012}}</ref>

